<tr>
<td class=3D"dwt-content">
<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->
<p>A magnetic field is a vector field which surrounds magnets and electric =
currents,=20
and is detected by the force it exerts on moving electric charges and on ma=
gnetic=20
materials. When placed in a magnetic field, magnetic dipoles tend to align =
their=20
axes parallel to the magnetic field. Magnetic fields also have their own en=
ergy=20
with an energy density proportional to the square of the field intensity.</=
p>
<p>For the physics of magnetic materials, see magnetism and magnet, and mor=
e specifically=20
ferromagnetism, paramagnetism, and diamagnetism. For constant magnetic fiel=
ds, such=20
as are generated by magnetic materials and steady currents, see magnetostat=
ics.=20
A changing electric field results in a magnetic field, and a changing magne=
tic field=20
also generates a electric field (see electromagnetism). </p>
<p>In special relativity, the electric field and magnetic field are two int=
errelated=20
aspects of a single object, called the electromagnetic field. A pure electr=
ic field=20
in one reference frame is observed as a combination of both an electric fie=
ld and=20
a magnetic field in a moving reference frame. - Wikipedia</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center"><strong>Standard unit =3D Tesla (T)</strong=
></p>
